  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency response to address malnutrition through improved nutrition, mental health and care practices, and water, hygiene and sanitation in Maungdaw District, Rakhine State</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The protracted acute humanitarian crisis in Maungdaw District, Rakhine State continues to worsen since communal violence erupted in June 2012. After decades of restriction on movements, compounded by ongoing inter-communal tensions in the area and limited access to basic services and livelihoods, the vulnerability to nutrition insecurity remains extremely high among the population. The gap in essential services coverage is particularly severe. Life-saving interventions are continuously needed as noted in the 2017 Humanitarian Response Plan. 

The violence that took place in Maungdaw District last October has resulted in further worsening of the humanitarian situation with additional IDPs and, a significant increase of children and women in need of appropriate treatment of acute malnutrition, healthcare and access to WASH essential commodities. The poor physical and mental health among both Pregnant and Lactating Women (PLW) and other caretakers directly contributes to worsening maternal and child care, affecting nutrition status and morbidity rates.
 
To address this situation, ACF&#x2019;s proposed intervention is twofold:
- Using a holistic approach to malnutrition through treatment, detection and prevention in Outpatient Therapeutic Program (OTPs) and Stabilization Centres (SCs inpatient), including follow-up of SAM children and acutely malnourished PLWs, with an integrated Mental Health and Care Practices (MHCP) component to strengthen positive care practices, such as Infant and Young Child Feeding (IYCF) practices, and provide beneficiaries with a safer hygiene environment. At community level, ACF will foster resilience and improve collaboration with authorities, the Ministry of Health and community health care leaders by working to incorporate nutrition specific interventions in their regular activities, through trainings on screening/referrals and a community mobilization strategy.
- Targeted, integrated WASH intervention, including hygiene promotion in OTPs, SCs and at community level, coupled with distributions of Caretaker and child WASH kits.</narrative>
  </description>
